hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider the 10-dimensional real projective space, denoted as $\mathbb{R}P^{10}$. It is a fundamental result in algebraic topology that its singular cohomology groups with coefficients in the field of two elements, $\mathbb{Z}_2$, are given by:
$$
H^i(\mathbb{R}P^{10}; \mathbb{Z}_2) \cong 
\begin{cases} 
\mathbb{Z}_2 & \text{for } 0 \le i \le 10 \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$
The direct sum of these groups forms the cohomology ring $H^*(\mathbb{R}P^{10}; \mathbb{Z}_2) = \bigoplus_{i=0}^{10} H^i(\mathbb{R}P^{10}; \mathbb{Z}_2)$, where the multiplication is defined by the cup product $\smile$.

Let $\alpha$ be the unique non-zero element in the first cohomology group, $H^1(\mathbb{R}P^{10}; \mathbb{Z}_2)$. We can form powers of this element, $\alpha^k = \underbrace{\alpha \smile \dots \smile \alpha}_{k \text{ times}}$, which is an element of $H^k(\mathbb{R}P^{10}; \mathbb{Z}_2)$. Determine the largest integer $k \ge 1$ for which the element $\alpha^k$ is non-zero.
